segments.text: As I recall, Gine Hall, a Greek type of building with columns in front, and they had plays and musicals and so forth there.
And I would go to the entertainment there to Gine Hall.
Did Aggies make noise in Gine sometimes?
Yes, I'm sure they did.
I'm sure they did.
So you're going home from your freshman year feeling good.
Right.
What did you do that summer?
That summer, I wanted to get experience in the oil field, so I went to Mr. McGowan and I said, I want to get a job to get some experience in the oil and gas industry.
So he sent me to a compressor station they had at Latex, Texas.
My first job was as an assistant in a machine shop.
I cleaned up stuff.
I remember the guy who ran the lathe and so forth.
I tried to learn things from him, but it was a dirty job.
very dirty job, but I wanted to be as macho as I could be.
I remember Mr. McGahn had a daughter who was a good friend of the girl I had gone with in Byrd High School.
They came out to see me at three o'clock one afternoon, and I was so embarrassed that
these girls would come out there and destroy my macho image.
And then at the last of the summer, though, I played tennis at Texas A&M, and I had aspirations to be a
I went to tennis tournaments for the last part of the summer, but I had gotten in some experience in the compressive station.
So you come back in the fall of 34 as a sophomore.
Right.
How was life better for a sophomore?
Oh, it was much better.
You didn't run errands.
You had the fish to run errands for you.
You had a certain amount of status.
You knew the ropes, and you had made friends.
Anyway, as opposed to your freshman year when everything was so uncertain about
whether you could survive or not, why, here you are in control.
Did you use a paddle?
Oh yes, oh yes, yes.
Where did you get your paddle?
I think, actually, Hudson and I shared it.
I think Hudson brought it from Shreveport, and we shared his paddle, isn't that right?
Still didn't have a car?
No, still had no car.
And what was your task in your outfit as a sophomore?
Did you have any?
As a sophomore, I was a corporal, and we actually were in charge of the
But I went out for cross country my sophomore year under Colonel Anderson.
And that took a lot of time, and then played basketball under Coach Reed.
And then I played tennis under Coach, under J.P. Abbott.
And then the classes became more interesting, geology and
And I really enjoyed the English classes under, and that's when I won the sophomore writing contest.
Was that under Dr. Abbott?
Was he your English?
He was my English prof, but actually the ones that decided it was a three-man panel, I think, that decided who won the $25.
Geology, who were some?
faculty members that were?
Let me see.
I remember, Torium Engineering, Harold Vance was the, and he had a lot of influence on not only me, but a lot of people.
And Vance was head of the Torium Engineering Department.
And he taught
as much philosophy as anything.
And people, outstanding people like Bum Bright and so forth, have really... Have you talked to Bum, incidentally?
He's worth talking to.
He'll tell you about his experience with Vance.
But Vance made a...
I mean, his philosophy about life and
so forth, had more effect than really your classes.
But he was a graduate of Stanford.
But A&M's Pretoria Engineering School has always been tops in the country.
When you got into the real world of petroleum engineering, did you find that A&M had prepared you well?
Oh yes, I sure did.
I thought
The combination of A&M and MIT, I was glad I went to MIT.
MIT, it was a different culture, of course, but A&M,
had the reputation which with me stuck in that you had a good basic knowledge of physics, of math, and so and also the ability to get along with other men that and I found out that
various companies that A&M's reputation was that people had a good basic educational foundation and they didn't mind getting their hands dirty and they got along well with other guys.
I've heard from others, wonder if you agree with this, A&M has always been strong in the real and
And schools like MIT in the theoretical.
Exactly, that's absolutely true.
You found that to be true?
Oh yeah, that's absolutely true.
Was there anything, when you got into the real world petroleum industry, was there anything that A&M had overlooked?
I'd say the
It was something that, educational-wise, I don't think so.
I think A&M had prepared you for the real world pretty good.
During your four years at A&M, describe the student body in general.
Where did they come from?
What kinds of families?
Background?
Money or lack of money?
I'd say for the most, the students at A&M were people who really wanted to get an education.
That was the controlling thing.
Some came from moneyed families, but most of them didn't.
I'd say certainly more than half of them worked in the mess hall or did other things.
But the common denominator was that these people wanted an education.
And one of the people in my class was a guy named Anderson, I remember.
He actually came, he hoboed into College Station on a freight train, but he had some sort of a federal assistance program he was on.
And this guy later ended up
working on the atomic bomb in Alamogarda.
Here's a guy who comes in on a freight train.
But the student body itself was...
I'd say the difference in A&M and most other schools was the fact that the
The principal purpose for their being there was to get an education as opposed to Texas, which let's say a lot of people go to Texas for their social life, at least at that time compared to A&M.
Were there kids from, most Aggies from small towns or rural or from the cities?
Small towns or rural mostly.
As I recall, somebody from
Highland Park was sort of an oddity, for instance.
Did y'all ever tease anybody about their being broke and not having any money?
No, because most people were broke themselves.
Did it matter whether you were a Catholic or a Baptist or a Jew?
Well, no, I think that's one of the things about A&M is that a person was accepted for what he was.
And I think you respected other people's faiths.
They had various organizations like the Hillel Club and the Catholic Clubs and so forth.
And people, their faiths were never
were never even questioned, as I recall.
And a guy who, and let's say when people elected class officers or something, it wasn't some moneyed guy, it was how he was viewed by his peers.
Did you all have religious emphasis weak then?
I'm not sure we did, the religious week as such, except that we... Did you participate in any Sunday activities?
Oh, yes, yes.
I was a, my, I was, earlier was a Methodist, my mother was a Methodist, but then I joined the Presbyterian Church, and so I used to go to services there, the Presbyterian services.
And where were they held?
I think in Bryan at that time, I'm not sure.
But I remember I used to go to the services.
We got there just as the new church in Bryan was opening.
Is that right?
The old one downtown was still there.
Is that right?
And I saved one of the pews that was in the truck to be taken to the dump.
Is that right?
And then gave it back to them about four years ago.
And I still have one of the...
light fixtures.
Is that right?
That was also in the tribe.
Is that right?
Now Colonel Andy was a Presbyterian.
Right.
Were there any student church related groups that met on campus?
Yeah, I think there were.
I think there were.
I think certainly the Jewish boys, I think, met on campus.
I'm not sure about the Catholics, but I think the Protestants went into Brine, but I'm not sure about that.
Now, at Northgate, what churches were already there?
I'm not sure.
I'm not sure.
Were there any Hispanic students?
Mexican-American?
Oh, yes.
Yes.
There were a number of Hispanic students.
Nothing like now, but there were a number of Hispanic students.
How were they treated?
Just like anybody else.
What you were, you know.
Were there any international students in your years?
Some, but they were quite few, the international.
But I remember in my class, Eddie Longoria was a classmate of mine, and his family was big in banking in Mexico.
And I remember a guy named Josephi was in my class, and his family had a ranch in Mexico.
And Eddie was a quarter mile on the track team, Eddie LaGoria.
But anybody was regarded on what he was, what he did.
Now, the Depression was hitting everybody hard.
Right.
Had the project houses started?
while you were there?
Those at the south of Kyle Field where the country boys lived?
I don't think so.
I don't think so.
I think, as I recall, everybody lived in the different halls, you know, at Hart Hall and Purr Year and so forth.
Now south of Hart Hall
And where the MSC is now, there are lots of faculty and staff houses.
Right.
Did you students ever go over in that area?
Yes, as a matter of fact, I remember J.P. Abbott invited the tennis team for dinner at his place.
Oh, describe that.
Describe what a faculty house was like then.
Well, it was a frame house, relatively small,
J.P. Abbott was a graduate of Vanderbilt, and I think his wife was, too.
Very charming southern people, very hospitable.
And I remember we had dinner, and tablecloth, napkins, loved beautiful silver, and which
You know, after eating in the mess hall was a real treat.
But anyway, the faculty houses somewhat reminded me of when I visited my uncle in Fort Robinson, Nebraska, of the different houses of the captains, the majors, and so forth, all according to rank.
The students never pulled any pranks over on a faculty or staff house?
Not that I knew of.
Not that I know of at all.
When did you and your buddies discover there were steam tunnels on the campus?
There were what?
Steam tunnels.
I don't think I ever did.
Oh, really?
No.
Oh?
No, I don't think I ever did.
I never knew of it.
They're big.
These are about six by eight foot tunnels.
Now, of course, they're all locked and screened off.
But after World War II, that would be the way where you went from one door to another.
Well, they weren't there.
At least I never heard of them, as a matter of fact.
The campus organizations that had the highest prestige
I presume the Corps would be the first one.
Of all of the student leadership positions on the campus, which one would have been the most respected?
Would it be Corps Commander?
Yes, the Corps Commander.
And then maybe second the captain of the football team.
But then in the military, after the Corps Commander,
the most prestigious things were to be your CO of your company or your battery, your captain of your company or your battery.
And those were
highly competitive jobs or offices, let's say, that were decided after your experience at camp, which was your junior year.
And then the military officers picked who would be captain of
of each outfit.
Were those people selected usually on a fair basis?
Oh, yeah.
Oh, yeah.
Like I said, it was a very competitive thing.
Actually, in my battery, the two of us really were competing to be captain of E Battery, Fred Silvey, and he and I ended up as roommates.
I know that Fred wanted that position, but he took it in stride and he was on the staff
How did you learn you had been selected?
How did you get that information?
As I recall, it was published.
It was published.
So nobody told you in advance?
Nobody to know.
It was published in orders.
What did your outfit buddies do to you after that?
After...
Didn't they play some kind of joke on you or something?
I don't remember, really, other than I think there were six of us who were officers in E Battery.
I think all I did was
congratulating me, that was all.
They didn't drown you out that night?
No, they didn't drown me out, no.
Describe the duties of a company commander.
What did you have to do during that year?
A company commander actually looked after his entire unit.
He was responsible for the
welfare of everybody in his unit and of individual things, like he approved passes for them to go on the weekend.
He kept up with their academics and that he saw that there was discipline in his outfit.
in conference with the rest of the seniors, and the seniors really ran the school at that time, and in conference with other seniors established what the disciplines would be, and really sort of
and sort of controlled hazing to a certain extent.
But when Colonel Andy came in, Colonel Andy had decided to cut out the board, and I was not the only one affected.
I think some others also got busted for a while and got reinstated.
what were some of the fun things, contrast the high and low points of being a company commander?
What were some of the joys and the
But some of the joys was actually leading your battery, your company, in reviews and also in your court trips, your marches down the street.
When you had special dances there where you invited your girlfriends down there while you were a big dog in the eyes of these gals.
Trying to deal with those sophomores that had used the board was a tough task.
What about
some other tough task that you had to do.
You actually carried out inspections of the different rooms and

And the Commandant, of course, would carry out inspections on a monthly basis or so, but you yourself carried out inspections in the meantime to be sure that they were... And you saw that the orders were
were followed that the commandant put out, as a matter of fact.
And you were responsible for that, which you did through the first sergeant and so forth.
But the chain of command was, I think, was one of the best educational things that I saw.
What did you and your buddies think about the yell leaders, the singing cadets, the band?
We respected and liked all of them.
Like singing the cadets, we thought that was great.
The band was held in very high respect and it was sort of special to be in the band.
here at A&M without a music school that was able to put on a first class band.
Excuse me, just let me call some guy.
We were talking about organizations and so on.
Yes.
What did you and your buddies, what about the Yell Eaters?
Was that a high prestige?
Oh yeah, it was a very high prestige thing.
Yeah, it was a very high prestige thing.
And the guy, the Yale leader, I forget whether they were elected or not, but it was a high prestige.
Were you aware that there were secret fraternities in existence at that time?
Yeah, yeah.
Which ones were there as far as you know?
There was something called Stickers and one called, well, let's see, Stickers and...
T.T.?
T.T.s, T.T.s, right.
As far as you were aware, which one had higher prestige?
Well, the TTs were the...
I'd say they had different statuses.
The TTs were
actually more social guys.
The stickers were more the athletic people.
And they had different, I'd say, different types of a
Of reputation.
Did the average student know there were secretaries?
No, no.
Okay.
The, let's see, dates.
How did you and your buddies get dates?
Well, in the case of, one of the ways was with the CIA.
When I was president of the sophomore class, I corresponded with the president of the sophomore class at CIA, and we set up a deal for the CIA girls to come down at a particular dance.
And so that was one way.
How were they treated at that dance?
like Queens.
They'd evacuate a building for them, a hall, they'd evacuate a hall for them, and they were treated like Queens.
I mean, I've heard girls say, you've never really known popularity until you've gone to an A&M dance.
Now, did you meet a special young lady while you were an undergraduate that
you would later marry?
No, no.
I met, when I was a senior, I remember a girl named Lillian Street, and her brother was in my battery, as a matter of fact.
And she was from San Antonio.
She came up to the dances and so forth, the senior dances as my date.
And she later married one of the guys in my outfit.
What were the student indulgences then?
What did people smoke and drink?
A lot of people smoked.
I never did.
I was always out for some team, and you couldn't smoke, and I never wanted to.
People drank a lot more hard liquor then than they now, as I understand it, kids drink beer mostly.
But actually, people would, guys would pool their resources when they'd maybe buy a bottle of gin or something like that.
Where did they buy it?
Well, this was when they'd leave the campus.
I mean, go to Houston.
Was there a place out toward Snook?
Was Whiskey Bridge?
I think there was.
I never did buy any liquor while I was at the campus, always Houston or Dallas or wherever.
Did you ever have any problem when you were company commander with somebody in the outfit with liquor in their room or beer?
I don't recall having any problem there.
I don't.
All right.
People smoked cigarettes?
Oh, yeah.
Cigars?
A lot of people smoked cigarettes and cigars.
Pipe?
Pipe and so forth.
Chewing tobacco or snorting?
Chewing tobacco, yes.
As a matter of fact, I think the fish had, at the first baseball game,
all had to chew tobacco.
It made everybody sick.
Most of them made everybody sick.
Had you and your buddies ever heard of the words marijuana or heroin?
No, never even heard of it at that time.
It was a simpler era.
Right.
Who were the famous people, the celebrities on the campus then?
Who was president when you got there?
Dr. Walton.
Describe him.
Dr. T.O.
Walton, a bald-headed guy who was in the, I forget at what time, the administration building I think had just been built, which is the column building.
The new .
Yeah, right, right.
But Dr. Walton was looked on as almost untouchable.
He was the big guru on the campus.
But the deans were also, I'd say, looked on with a certain amount of awe and respect.
Who was engineering?
Dean Bolton was the dean of engineering, and he determined whether you were a distinguished student or not.
The different deans of the colleges did.
I remember Dean Brooks was the head of liberal arts by being roomy with Hudson Van Lone, who used to go see Dean Brooks about every two months.
Thank you.
